'''Malton Castle''' was a castle in [[Malton, North Yorkshire]], England. A wooden motte and bailey castle was built by William Tyson, lord of Alnwick in the 11th century. The castle was given to [[Eustace fitz John]], who rebuilt it in stone.<ref>{{cite news|title=Keeping Malton Castleâ€™s story alive|url=http://www.gazetteherald.co.uk/features/features/11182573.Keeping_Malton_Castle___s_story_alive/|accessdate=5 October 2016|work=Gazette & Herald|date=30 April 2014}}</ref>
Eustace negotiated the delivery of the castle to King [[David I of Scotland]] in 1138. The Scots garrisoned the castle, however it was captured later the same year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Parishes: New Malton|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/yorks/north/vol1/pp529-537|website=British History Online|accessdate=5 October 2016}}</ref> King [[Richard I of England]] visited the castle in 1189 and King [[Edward II of England]] in 1307. The castle was held against King [[John, King of England|John of England]], during the [[First Barons' War]]. After the [[battle of Old Byland]] the castle was captured and destroyed by King [[Robert I of Scotland]] in 1322.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pettifer|first1=Adrian|title=English castles: a guide by counties|date=1995|publisher=Boydell Press|location=Woodbridge|isbn=9780851156002|page=301|chapter=Yorkshire: North Riding}}</ref> The castle was not repaired and fell into ruins.
A house was built on the site in 1569 by Ralph, Lord Eure, which came to be inherited by two sisters of the Eure family, Margaret and Mary. In 1674 they fell out over ownership and took their argument to the County Sheriff, who destroyed the house and put the stones into two equal piles for the sisters to share.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stone|first1=John|title=Field of change|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/northyorkshire/content/articles/2008/06/02/castle_garden_history_feature.shtml|website=BBC York & North Yorkshire|accessdate=5 October 2016|date=2 June 2008}}</ref>
